value.value: The name assigned to a medicinal product as approved by a regulatory authority of the country of authorization.

label.value: Medicines And Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency

value.value: A government agency of the United Kingdom responsible for ensuring that medicines and medical devices work, and are acceptably safe. (MHRA)
A type of clinical trial in which 10,000 or more subjects are enrolled.

A family of enveloped, double-stranded DNA viruses that infect mammals, birds, and insects. It is divided into two subfamilies: chordopoxvirinae, poxviruses of vertebrates, and entomopoxvirinae, poxviruses of insects.
Required or expected data that is not present, which may be due to non-completion or corruption.
A clinical study that is being conducted at multiple locations.
Spoken or written language as used in ordinary communications between individuals and groups.

Pharmaceutical data received from factual, observational sources such as adverse event reports, clinical or post-approval studies or other scientific studies about a severe or unexpected severe hazard related to the pharmaceutical after approval or following the most recent assessment of the drug.

A clinical trial that uses a single individual as the entire study population. This subject receives different treatments and control treatments with the goal of determining the best intervention for an individual patient using objective data-driven criteria.

A statistical method to test if observations are significant or due to chance. It proposes that no statistical significance exists in a set of given observations and attempts to show that no variation exists between variables or that a single variable is no different than its mean. It is presumed to be true until statistical evidence nullifies it for an alternative hypothesis.
A set of ten ethical principles for human experimentation established as a result of the Nuremberg trials at the end of the Second World War.
Ayn measurement that is not subject to observer assessment, such as those registered by an instrument.
Any assessment made by an observer, as opposed to a device.
The taxonomic order of mammals that includes man, monkeys, and lemurs.
A clinical outcome assessment that is reported by someone other than the patient or a healthcare professional.
An indication that a study is able to add subjects.
A design model that lays out how a study will be carried out in order to fulfill its objectives.
The values reported in the initial documents used to record study data.
A subject selection method whereby subjects with similar characteristics are assigned as a pair, with the intention that each will receive different treatment within the course of the clinical trial.
A case report form that is printed on paper.
A system for computer access control that requires a user to create a new password at set intervals.
A file containing demographic, medical, and treatment information pertaining to an individual patient.
The prompt, question or instruction in a patient-reported outcome item. (CDISC Glossary)
A question, statement, or task and its pre-specified response values within a patient-reported outcome instrument.

Organisms without a cell nucleus or any other membrane-bound organelles. Most prokaryotes are bacteria but the group includes both the Bacteria and the Archaea. Eukaryota, Bacteria, and Archaea are now considered the top nodes of a three-domain taxonomy system.
The process for identifying the individual questions, statements, or tasks within a patient reported outcome (PRO) instrument.
A document or collection or documents that contain a patient-reported survey (e.g., questionnaire) in addition to the information and instructions that document how to use the survey.
A clinical outcome assessment in which a task is performed by a subject under the administration of a healthcare professional.
A change which occurs at a particular time, affecting all age groups and cohorts uniformly.
Data that is not, under normal circumstances, subject to change.

The set of data generated by the subset of subjects who complied with the protocol sufficiently to ensure that these data would be likely to exhibit the effects of treatment according to the underlying scientific model. (ICH)
A scientific discipline, and subdivision of Health Economics, that compares one pharmaceutical product or treatment to another with respect to various cost comparison measures.
Surveillance of drug performance, including detection, monitoring, and prevention of adverse effects by substances with pharmacological activity.
Any intended, protocol-defined activity involving data collection from a study subject.
A candidate's agreement to carry out investigations or trials that are not required by any legal provision.
Various members of the family Leporidae, especially those of the genus Sylvilagus.
Programs to identify adverse events that did not appear during the drug approval process.
A study designed to test the effectiveness of an intervention in a broad routine clinical practice.
An investigation that tests a drug, procedure or medical treatment in animals to determine any toxic effects before trials can be carried out in humans.
The date on which the last clinical study subject was given the final intervention or examination in order to obtain information to support the primary outcome.
The study outcome factor of greatest priority that contributes to the main objective of the trial.
A variable that directly or indirectly impacts the outcome of a clinical trial.
A type of study in which participants are enrolled into the study before they develop the disease or outcome in question.
Any representation of information that permits the identity of an individual to whom the information applies to be reasonably inferred by either direct or indirect means.
An indication that the sponsor, including all reviewers, have approved the protocol.
Any documentation that pertains to the further understanding of a study protocol.
An amphibian in the order Anura, which includes the toads. The commonest frog genera are Rana (grass frogs) and Hyla (tree frogs).
A citation to a publication that is significantly related to a study protocol.
An indication that the source of clinical trial data comes from a person other than the subject.
